data.content:
Here's the mapping:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture's `Dispose` |

The one-time setup/teardown moves into a **shared fixture class**. Your test class receives it via `IClassFixture<T>` and constructor injection.

```csharp
// Shared fixture handles one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // replaces [OneTimeSetUp]
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // replaces [OneTimeTearDown]
    }
}

// No [TestFixture] attribute needed in xUnit
public class CustomerRepositoryTests
    : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp] — runs before each test
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable.Dispose replaces [TearDown] — runs after each test
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]   // replaces [Test]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key differences to note:
- **xUnit creates a new class instance per test**, so the constructor/`Dispose` naturally bracket each test — no attributes needed.
- The `DatabaseFixture` is instantiated **once** and shared across all tests in the class via the `IClassFixture<T>` interface.
- If you need to share the fixture across **multiple** test classes, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` with a `[Collection]` attribute instead.
